At this point we all know what Linear Regression is.. if not.. then well.. ok I'll explain in short. (We are gonna dive deeper later anyway)

Say you have data of heights and weights of different dogs. You plot them on a graph to see if there is any relation between them..

![image.png](data:image/png;base64,)

on closer inspection you see the relation mostly seems to be a linear- i.e., weight increase proportionately with height. 

one thing we know for sure is that Machine Learning is basically maths and using maths to recognise pattern in the data, we noticed the pattern (linear).. what's the math?

You say Linear! I hear Line. You say Linear! I hear Line. Yeah, it means line. See the image below, the data fits roughly on a Line. 

![image.png](data:image/png;base64,)

The equation for a line is: $y = mx + c$

Thats it, this is the basic concept of Linear Regression, see if the data fits on a line- if yes.. then question arrises how to find the ideal line. 

## Loss Functions:
Sum of least squares / Sum of squared residuals:

$$SSR = \sum_{i=0}^n (y_i - \hat{y_i})^2$$

*here, $y_i =$ actual $y$ value of the ${i^{th}}$ data point and ${\hat{y_i}=}$ predicted/output value of the line for the  ${i^{th}}$ data point.*
